What is the Global Citizen Festival, and has it managed to reduce poverty?
Saturday, the annual music event, the Global Citizen Festival, kicks off in New York City, where world-class musicians will perform to stand up for a truly noble cause: the global eradication of poverty.
Now in its seventh year, the Global Citizen Festival is expected to draw tens of thousands of people to the Great Plaza in Central Park, where participants will not only enjoy Janet Jackson, Cardi B or Shawn Mendes's performances, but also draw attention to the event's real purpose: to end extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival was first organised in 2012 as part of the Global Poverty Project, run by an international advocacy group that aims to eradicate poverty by engaging more people in the active fight against poverty.
Free tickets to the concert are available to those (unless they are willing to pay for a VIP ticket) who undertake certain tasks or actions, such as volunteering, sending an e-mail to a leading politician, making a phone call, or any other meaningful activity that can draw attention to the project's goal of eradicating poverty.
But how successful has Global Citizen actually been in achieving its goals over the past 12 years?
Is it really an effective way to reward people with concert tickets to convince others that action is needed, or is it just another form of what's called "clicktivism", where people feel they've made a meaningful contribution to a cause by signing an online petition or writing a Twitter message?
Since 2011, more than 19 million actions have been carried out by project sponsors, according to Global Citizen data, serving a wide range of purposes.
According to the organization, these actions have helped world leaders allocate $37 billion to policies and commitments to fight poverty, which could affect the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group claimed 390 commitments and announcements that stemmed from their actions, of which $10 billion had already been paid or raised through fundraising.
The group estimates that the money raised has already directly affected the lives of nearly 649 million people.
Among the key commitments is The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based partnership of investors and developers aimed at helping children reach their potential.The organization pledged $35 million to help end hunger in Rwanda after receiving more than 4,700 Twitter messages from "global citizens".
"With the support of the UK government, and the support of donors, national governments and global citizens like you, we can eradicate social injustice and malnutrition from the history books", said Tracey Ullman, ambassador for Power of Nutrition, to the crowd at a live concert in London in April 2018.
The group also claims that after more than 5,000 actions to call on the UK to improve nutrition for mothers and their children, the government has allocated funds for the Power of Nutrition project, which will improve the nutrition of 5 million women and children.
One of the frequently asked questions posted on the Global Citizen website is: Why do you think that extreme poverty can be eradicated?
According to Global Citizen, "It's going to be a long and difficult journey, one that sometimes gets stuck and sometimes fails.
But like the civil rights and anti-segregation movements of the past, we will achieve our goal because together we are stronger.
