Red tide news: decreasing concentrations in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red wave concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
FWC reports more spotted blooms from Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentration.
The red tide extends for about 130 miles along the coast from Pinellas County in the north to Lee County in the south.
There are spots about 10 miles outside Hillsborough County, but in a relatively small area compared to last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, moderate concentrations were reported in Pinellas County and along its shores, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County and along its coast, background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations in Lee County and along its coast, and low concentrations in Collier County.
There have been continued reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation reported from northwest Florida last week.
